  "market_context": "On 25 Jan 2024, ETH was in an uptrend on the hourly chart. A 5-minute structure shift appeared bearish (lower high formed), but the analyst identified it as a retracement into an hourly fair value gap, not a true trend reversal.",
  "key_observation": "The apparent 5-minute market structure shift (lower high) failed because price was retracing into a higher-time-frame hourly fair value gap, which acted as support and caused price to resume the uptrend.",
  "analysis_steps": [
    "Step 1: On the 5-minute ETH chart, the analyst identified a potential bearish structure shift with a lower high forming after a displacement down.",
    "Step 2: The analyst zoomed out to the hourly chart and marked a fair value gap (FVG) that price was approaching on the 5-minute timeframe.",
    "Step 3: The analyst concluded the 5-minute 'shift' was merely a retracement into the hourly FVG, not a valid trend change, and therefore the bearish setup would fail.",
    "Step 4: The analyst emphasized trading with the higher-time-frame bias—expecting price to respect the hourly FVG as support and continue higher."
  ],
  "outcome": "The retracement failed; price rejected the 5-minute lower high and resumed upward toward the hourly FVG zone and beyond.",
  "lessons": "A lower-time-frame structure shift must be validated against higher-time-frame price delivery arrays (e.g., FVGs). Retracements into HTF imbalances often fail as reversals and instead act as continuation zones.",
